Part 3

Hypothesis:

Based on what the graphs seem to show, mainly the histograms, it can be said that the Close_ETF column shows a little right skew to the normal distribution whilst the other three columns are normally distributed.

In [10]:
#create Q-Q plot for all columns
qqnorm(data_raw$Close_ETF)
qqline(data_raw$Close_ETF)

qqnorm(data_raw$oil)
qqline(data_raw$oil)

qqnorm(data_raw$gold)
qqline(data_raw$gold)

qqnorm(data_raw$JPM)
qqline(data_raw$JPM)

Based on the QQ test performed on all columns, we can state that since each graph closely falls around the normal distribution line, that each of these three variables show a normal distribution.

From the residuals vs. fitted plot we can see that the mean is 0 since the red line is horizontal at y value 0.

Since there is no cone shape present within the graph among the blue circles, we can state that the variance is constant.

The points fall along the best fit line for normality in the QQ plot hence we can state that this data is normally distributed.

The independence assumption is not met because there seems to be a clear relationship between the residuals and fitted values. There is a linear relationship.

To improve the quality of the regression model we can increase the number of interaction terms. For example, in part 9 we said Oil + Gold. Where as we could say Oil * Gold to increase the interactions between the columns to produce a more comprehensive regression model. You can also add a MARS or multivariate adaptive regression spline. This line fits nonparametric models and can be used to fit data that doesnt follow a linear regression but instead follow a nonparametric regression. We could fit isotonic regression to remove any assumption of the target function form. An advantage of isotonic regression is that its not contrained by any functional form as long as the function is monotonic increasing. It can also be used iteratively to fit ideal distances to preserve relative dissimalrity order. Adding spines
